05348nam a22007215i 9780822379782DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t19951995ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1229161827  a97808223797827 a10.1515/97808223797822doi  a(DE-B1597)552179  a(OCoLC)1226679576  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aR724b.T68 1995 7aMED0500002bisacsh04a174/.200aTroubled Bodies :bCritical Perspectives on Postmodernism, Medical Ethics, and the Body /ced. by Paul A. Komesaroff. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1995] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: postmodern medical ethics? -- tDivide and multiply: culture and politics in the new medical order -- tAbortion and embodiment -- tFrom bioethics to microethics: ethical debate and clinical medicine -- tScience, medicine, and illness: rediscovering the patient as a person -- tThe body politic -- tWhose body? Feminist views on reproductive technology -- tMaking babies, making sense: reproductive technologies, postmodernity, and the ambiguities of feminism -- tBodies and subjects: medical ethics and feminism -- tThe body biomedical ethics forgets -- tFemale bodies and food: a case of ethics and psychiatry -- tGlossary -- tIndex -- tNotes on Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSetting out the implications of the postmodern condition for medical ethics, Troubled Bodies challenges the contemporary paradigms of medical ethics and reconceptualizes the nature of the field. Drawing on recent developments in philosophy, philosophy of science, and feminist theory, this volume seeks to expand familiar ethical reflections on medicine to incorporate new ways of thinking about the body and the dilemmas raised by recent developments in medical techniques.These essays examine the ways in which the consideration of ethical questions is shaped by the structures of knowledge and communication at work in clinical practice, by current assumptions regarding the concept of the body, and by the social and political implications of both. Representing various perspectives including medicine, nursing, philosophy, and sociology, these essays look anew at issues of abortion, reproductive technologies, the doctor-patient relationship, the social construction of illness, the cultural assumptions and consequences of medicine, and the theoretical presuppositions underlying modern psychiatry. Diverging from the tenets of mainstream bioethics, Troubled Bodies suggests that, rather than searching for the correct "coherent perspective" from which to draw ethical principles, we must apprehend the complexity and diversity of the discursive systems within which we dwell.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aBioethics. 0aFeminist theory. 0aMedical ethics. 0aPostmodernism. 0aWomenxHealth and hygiene. 7aMEDICAL / Ethics.2bisacsh1 aCaddick, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharlesworth, Max, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiprose, Rosalyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomesaroff, Paul A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomesaroff, Paul A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMackenzie, Catriona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRedding, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRothfield, Philipa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRussell, Deni